<TEXT>
a federal appeals court panel friday upheld 
texas countywide elections for judges ruling 21 that black 
voting strength isnt illegally diluted by electing as many as 59 
judges at large from one county 
the threejudge panel of the 5th us circuit court of appeals 
overturned us district judge lucius buntons decision that the 
elections in nine urban texas counties illegally dilute the 
strength of minority voters 
while elected judges are representatives in that they are 
accountable to a constituency of electors the full authority of a 
trial judges office is exercised exclusively by one individual 
and there can be no share of such a singlemember office the 
panel said in its decision consequently the countywide election 
of district court judges does not violate the voting rights act 
bunton ruling last november on a lawsuit by the league of 
united latin american citizens ordered texas to divide the nine 
counties into electoral subdistricts and to hold nonpartisan 
elections in those districts 
bunton had directed the elections be held may 5 but the 
appellate court has stayed that order 
the counties which include dallas fort worth houston san 
antonio austin and four smaller cities elect 172 of texas 390 
district judges 
fridays decision is clearly good news for our judicial system 
and for the people of texas said gov bill clements by its 
decision today the panel ruled that texans will retain the right 
to elect all trial judges who serve in their local county 
courthouse 
as texas chief elections officer and a defendant in this 
lawsuit i am extremely pleased with this action said texas 
secretary of state george bayoud 
the league of united latin american citizens a major minority 
rights group based in san antonio didnt immediately return 
telephone calls seeking comment 
the losing side can petition the panel for a rehearing or 
appeal to the supreme court 
appeals judge sam d johnson of austin disagreed with the ruling 
by judge patrick higginbotham of dallas who voted with judge 
carolyn dineen king of houston 
i am totally at odds with the majoritys application of the 
socalled single officeholder exception johnson wrote in his 
dissent 
he said the majority incorrectly based its decision on a new 
york case involving three candidates elected from three different 
districts the majority expands this beyond its logical 
bounds wrote johnson 
under texas law district judges are elected every four years 
they run atlarge with all voters in a county allowed to vote in 
every race 
bunton said the atlarge elections deny hispanic and black 
voters an equal chance to elect the candidates they want 
the appellate panel rejected texas arguments that judges are 
not representatives and that congress didnt mean judicial 
elections to fall under the voting rights act 
but it also rejected the central argument brought by the league 
that each judge is part of a larger court which should have more 
black representatives 
indisputably district judges in texas share administrative 
tasks with other district judges in the same county it said 
equally indisputably however the district judge in texas does 
his judging alone 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

