<TEXT>
the pedestrian the most flexible inexpensive 
and pollutionfree unit of transportation is being driven into 
manhattan streets by sidewalk obstructions 
obstacles range from construction scaffolding to slowmoving 
outoftowners 
this becomes apparent on the west side of lexington avenue each 
weekday afternoon at 523 when according to scientific studies 
the sidewalk between 42nd and 43rd streets is the most crowded on 
the planet 
almost 160 pedestrians a minute squeeze through a channel 
usually narrowed to 4 feet by newspaper vending machines trash 
cans street and traffic light poles a newsstand a table selling 
exotic oils and incense a flower stand and a tank of refrigerated 
liquid nitrogen 
something has to give so the pedestrians step off the curb a 
few at first then more until at least a third of the thousands 
steaming toward grand central terminal are doing so in the dubious 
safety of the lexington avenue bus lane 
the pedestrian has been losing ground in the struggle for 
space in manhattan according to a report by the borough 
presidents office and that is a serious problem in an 
environment which depends so heavily on walking for its mobility 
another reminder of how serious a problem came last week 
erica moreno 3 was walking handinhand with her mother in 
40th street because a construction project had closed the sidewalk 
a driver lost control of his car and smashed another vehicle into 
the girl killing her 
each year cars and trucks in new york kill more than 600 
pedestrians and injure 15000 william h whyte an urban planner 
who has counted and studied pedestrians on lexington and streets 
all over the world says new yorkers try to bully cars with an 
attitude of make way for me or kill me 
but walking is vital on a crowded island where 60 percent of 
eligible adults dont even have a drivers license and whyte says 
pedestrians in manhattan walk longer and faster than any place in 
america 
they need space however and manhattans already congested 
streets and sidewalks have been tied up by the financial services 
boom of the 1980s which brought in more workers and the attendant 
construction boom which closed down more sidewalks 
then there are tourists a male new york pedestrians cruising 
speed can exceed 350 feet a minute visitors from less populous 
communities often move at 250 feet a minute and they have been 
seen doing so three abreast as a result locals are always walking 
up the heels of outoftowners 
but the biggest problem is the dimension and condition of the 
citys pedestrian infrastructure the sidewalks on lexington 
between 42nd and 60th much of the pavement is cracked or buckled 
sloping in spots at 20 degrees it is full of holes and hollows 
some with semipermanent puddles replenished by rain and snow in 
winter and by condensate from store air conditioners in summer 
at 12 feet lexingtons sidewalks are far narrower than fifth 
avenues 22 feet and they usually are further reduced by various 
obstacles traffic is reduced to one lane at the northwest corner 
of 60th by a subway entrance construction scaffolding and a 
newsstand selling everything but washing machines 
most of the space along lexington goes to vehicles even though 
the pedestrian volume at the lexington entrance to grand central is 
rivaled only by one approach to tokyos shinjuku rail station 
about 78 percent of the people moving along the avenue at peak 
periods are on foot only 22 percent are in vehicles yet only 34 
percent of the avenues total space is given to pedestrians 20 
percent of that usable while vehicles get 66 percent 
to pedestrians the solution seems obvious damn the motorists 
and widen the sidewalks the city plans the latter on sixth avenue 
above 42nd street where it will narrow each vehicular lane to add 
3 feet of sidewalk drivers and many businesses oppose such 
tactics but later this year a coalition of environmental groups 
will ask the city to begin a broad program of sidewalk expansion 
and reconstruction 
until that happens there will be more jaywalking more midblock 
crossing more people in the bus lane according to peter hecht of 
the project for public spaces who has filmed and studied 
pedestrian movements 
street walking he says is the pedestrians way of saying the 
sidewalks are too crowded theyre voting with their feet 
</TEXT>
