<TEXT>
poles once blamed the communists for 
shortages of everything from meat to gasoline but their newly won 
freedoms have produced a unique supply problem too few passports 
to meet the demand 
now that regulations have been loosened to allow poles to travel 
freely abroad there has been a rush to apply for passports which 
people can now keep at home 
this has resulted in a shortage of the passport documents 
themselves according to media reports 
a personnel shortage also has lengthened the waiting time for 
passports the prosolidarity daily gazeta wyborcza reported this 
week sometimes the wait is even longer than it took to obtain a 
passport when the communists were still in power 
a meeting at the interior ministry on tuesday failed to solve 
the problem the document shortage is blamed on the state mint 
which prints passports the newspaper said 
while the holiday season is approaching the lack of passports 
continues the interior ministry did not promise any rapid 
improvement gazeta wyborcza said 
negotiations are under way with a swiss firm to produce the 
travel documents but the 22 million price tag may prove too high 
for the financially strapped government the newspaper said 
in one warsaw district the wait for a passport now exceeds two 
months and the situation is similar across poland gazeta wyborcza 
said 
the issuance of passports is to be transferred from the interior 
ministry which controls the police and security forces to the 
civil administration under reforms pending in parliament 
but that shift which will take three months from the time the 
law is enacted is not expected to solve the shortage the 
newspaper said 
after martial law was lifted in 1983 communist authorities 
gradually eased restrictions on travel abroad and in many cases 
poles were able to receive a passport within several weeks of 
filing their application 
in early 1989 the thencommunist government lifted a regulation 
requiring poles to surrender their passport to police after every 
trip abroad and then reapply for the document when they wanted to 
travel again 
instead poles were allowed to keep their passport at home and 
the document remained valid for an unlimited number of trips abroad 
for up to 10 years 
the solidarityled government which came to power in august 
has further eased travel regulations 
the biggest problem now for poles wanting to travel west is 
obtaining a visa poles face long lines and must undergo a careful 
screening process in order to obtain visas for such popular 
destinations as britain and the united states 
