<DOCNO> AP900511-0018 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan is 
outlining ideas for overhauling the bank deposit insurance system 
but is stopping well short of advocating a substantial cutback in 
the 56yearold program 
in his first extensive remarks on the subject greenspan on 
thursday suggested 
varying insurance premiums according to the riskiness of a 
banks investments 
examining banks books more frequently 
seizing weak banks faster 
requiring bank owners to risk more of their own money 
federal deposit insurance began in 1934 after the nation 
suffered an unprecedented wave of bank runs and failures during the 
depression however it has been blamed for skewing incentives in 
the financial system and helping create the savings and loan crisis 
all banks now pay the same deposit insurance premium current 
law in most cases bars the takeover of banks until they officially 
are insolvent but by that time losses to the federal deposit 
insurance fund sometimes are steep 
greenspan in a speech in chicago did not address proposals on 
cutting back 100000 per account insurance limiting insurance to 
one account imposing deductibles on insurance or finding a way 
to let large banks fail without endangering the system 
he is proceeding gingerly but in the chairman are the 
seeds of a most radical reform of our existing financial system 
said kenneth a guenther executive vice president of the 
independent bankers association of america which represents 
smaller banks wary of deposit insurance changes 
the treasury department is due to release its banking reform 
plan by next february greenspan is expected to be a major 
influence in its development and in congressional debate on the 
issue next year 
the treasury study at greenspans insistence was required by 
last years legislation on bailing out the nations troubled 
savings and loans 
greenspan appeared to reject the notion of simply abolishing 
deposit insurance and other safeguards which some freemarket 
conservatives advocate 
the united states has not suffered a financial panic or 
systemic bank run in the last 50 years in large part this reflects 
the safety net he said 
but protection comes at a cost he said the threepart safety 
net poses a moral hazard for bankers by allowing them to shift 
some of the risks of their actions onto the public 
the three areas are deposit insurance the ability of banks to 
borrow at low rates in emergencies from the feds discount window 
and banks access the feds electronic payments wire which 
guarantees payments between banks 
reform of the safety net should be considered in tandem with 
permitting banks to expand into securities and insurance greenspan 
said 
offering banks no new powers likely would cause commercial 
banking to shrink shifting money to unprotected parts of the 
financial system that in turn may create systemic risk similar 
to that faced in earlier years he said 
some have advocated strict fire walls separating new 
activities from an insured bank but greenspan said that 
undercuts the reason for granting any additional powers to 
banking organizations in the first place 
instead we should probably develop additional 
marketsimulating ways of limiting moral hazard he said 
we might also consider the desirability of returning to 
capital requirements that more closely simulate those that the 
market dictated in a world without a safety net he said 
bank owners currently risk about six cents of every dollar they 
lend greenspan noted that in the 1800s before the creation of 
deposit insurance and the discount window bankers risked 25 cents 
to 50 cents for every dollar loaned that encouraged them to use 
more caution he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

