<TEXT>
a microbe that is a common contaminant in 
laboratories may be an infectious agent that contributes to the 
lethal effects of the aids virus 
the organism called mycoplasma was discovered four years ago 
by shyhching lo but is only now being considered seriously by 
aids investigators according to an article published today in the 
journal science 
lo a virologist at the armed forces institute of pathology 
here said in a telephone interview that his work was ignored until 
he presented his work last december and march at special workshops 
some of the worlds leading experts on mycoplasmas attended the 
workshops and at least four labs now are trying to confirm los 
work 
lo reported that in five years of study he has isolated a 
specific mycoplasma from the heart kidneys brain spleen and 
liver of aids patients he said the microbe which he calls 
mycoplasma incognitus is a new species that may also be able to 
independently cause disease 
dr john bartlett of johns hopkins university who sponsored lo 
at the march workshop said the findings are intriguing but 
that the research needs to be verified in other laboratories before 
it can be accepted widely 
whenever a researcher finds mycoplasmas the medical community 
tends to be skeptical said bartlett mycoplasmas frequently are 
found as contaminants in microbiological experiments he said 
im not convinced it is a cause of disease but it needs 
further study bartlett said of los study other researchers 
agreed 
lo first reported discovery of his mycoplasma in 1986 but the 
findings met with ridicule in the research community lo now 
acknowledges there was reason for skepticism the data were not 
very conclusive he said 
lo continued to work however and last year the american 
journal of tropical medicine published his first paper on 
mycoplasmas it captured new interest he said 
when we presented this work before it wasnt understood 
said lo now they have started a lot of work looking into it 
the findings were strong enough for the governments national 
institute of allergies and infectious diseases to convene a 
workshop last december in san antonio and allow lo to present his 
studies to some of the nations top microbiologists 
dr joel b baseman a microbiologist at the university of texas 
health science center in san antonio and chairman of the december 
workshop said los studies stood up to close scrutiny from experts 
in the field he said many went away convinced that lo had found 
enough evidence of a new infectious agent that further study was 
justified 
but just what role if any the mycoplasma plays in aids is not 
known 
its not absolutely clear what it is doing in aidsrelated 
disease but it appears to be present in many cases and seems to 
the sole source of pathology in specific tissues said baseman 
the evidence is reasonable 
science the journal of the american association for the 
advancement of science reported that luc montagnier a prominent 
french researcher and the codiscoverer of the human 
immunodeficiency virus or hiv believed to cause aids also has 
studied a mycoplasma in aids patients 
montagnier has speculated that a mycoplasma is an aids virus 
cofactor which means it works with hiv to cause disease 
a mycoplasma is neither a virus or a bacteria it has no cell 
wall but it contains genetic material and reproduces by division 
as does bacteria mycoplasmas have been associated with some rare 
types of pneumonia and have been isolated in the genital tract of 
healthy men and women 
baseman said lo in his workshop presentation showed that 
although the mycoplasma may play a role in aids it may be a lethal 
infection agent all by itself he said lo isolated the mycoplasma 
in six patients who tested negative for the aids virus but who 
died from unspecified causes within seven weeks of becoming ill 
four silvered leaf monkeys also died of unspecified disease 
within nine months of being injected with the mycoplasma science 
reported 
</TEXT>
