congressional analysts say a greater reliance 
on military reserves could save the united states 43 billion over 
several years by cutting active duty forces 
changes in threats to us security coupled with downward 
pressure on the defense budget suggest that the reserves may take 
on even greater importance robert reischauer director of the 
congressional budget office told a senate panel thursday 
under the proposed scenario active duty armed forces would be 
cut by 463000 down to 16 million the reduction would increase 
the share of the reserves in the total force from 36 percent to 42 
percent 
analysts presented their findings at a senate armed services 
committee hearing on increased use of the reserves at a time when 
the soviet threat to the west has diminished and constraints on the 
budget has grown 
in this period of increased warning time and fiscal austerity 
