the bill approved thursday would overhaul the hatch act the law 
was passed in 1939 in response to evidence that enrollees in the 
works progress administration were being required by new deal 
political appointees to donate to the reelection campaign of 
thensen alben barkley dky 
the legislation was sought by federal employee and postal unions 
after the reagan administration filed hatch act charges against 
three union presidents for endorsing democrat walter mondale in the 
1984 presidential election the charges were later dismissed by a 
federal appeals court 
because a permanent and professional civil service is 
wellestablished now democrats contended most of the hatch act 
restrictions are no longer needed 
sen brock adams said federal workers now enjoy fewer political 
rights under an archaic curtain of silence than people do in 
the emerging democracies of eastern europe 
republicans however contend the legislation will return the 
civil and postal services to a spoils system in which workers 
will be subtly coerced to take up political causes 
the bill would still prohibit federal workers from engaging in 
political activities while on the job and from running for public 
office or soliciting campaign funds from the public 
but they could in their off time begin holding office in local 
state and national political organizations attend their 
conventions as delegates and solicit campaign funds fromcoworkers 
on behalf of candidates or federal employee union political action 
committees 
the house passed by a vetoproof 29790 vote a year ago a 
similar but broader bill that also would remove the prohibitions on 
running for office and soliciting campaign funds 
before the senate vote thursday republicans made a stab at 
trying to continue the current restrictions on employees of the 
irs intelligence agencies the justice department and the federal 
election commission 
certain critical agencies of this government need to be beyond 
political involvement and not have any taint of politics or 
coercion said sen pete v domenici rnm 
his amendment to exempt employees of those agencies from the 
looser restrictions on political involvement and forbid government 
workers from soliciting coworkers for campaign funds was defeated 
on a 5839 vote 
the senate however did adopt on a 970 vote an amendment by 
dole that would maintain the current restrictions on the 240 
employees of the federal election commission 
