pipkin said thursday cause theres not any profit to be made 
this year 
pipkin and his brother grow wheat cotton soybeans and rice on 
about 1000 acres in the community where they grew up a few miles 
north of pine bluff in central arkansas their land handed down by 
their father is divided by the arkansas river levee about 250 
acres on the river side of the levee are under water 
you can walk down there and catch a fish if you want to 
said pipkin pointing to a spot where water swallows the road that 
used to cut across his wheat field 
pipkin said about half of his 100acre winter wheat crop is 
destroyed 
its going to hurt the yield no doubt about that he said 
id say after this we might cut half a crop 
and his cotton might not be planted at all 
its going to hurt us bad pipkin said if we get in any 
cotton its not going to have time to make enough like it should 
officials are estimating that 450000 acres of wheat statewide 
have been damaged by the flooding which could amount to a 48 
million loss rough estimates indicate 25000 to 30000 head of 
cattle were stranded by high water and many are presumed drowned 
in a letter thursday to president bush gov bill clinton said 
initial official estimates of damage to private nonagricultural 
property total 65 million 
according to preliminary state figures flooding has damaged 251 
homes but that number will go up as the water recedes said gary 
talley spokesman for the arkansas office of emergency services 
the flooding was touched off by last weeks severe storms which 
were blamed for 13 deaths one in oklahoma and the others in texas 
in texas estimated damage to agricultural production stands at 
500 million to 700 million with millions more to houses and 
roads 
arkansas farmers have been attacking the us army corps of 
engineers saying it had mismanaged dams at lake texoma on the 
red river and lake eufala in oklahoma on the arkansas 
after meeting with farmers along the red river on wednesday 
clinton said he would talk with members of arkansas congressional 
delegation about the possibility of forming a task force to study 
the corps flood management 
so many of them down there felt rightly or wrongly that the 
corps could have made different decisions on over the last few 
months and there would be less flooding clinton said 
the corps rebutted complaints that its discharges from rising 
lakes was too much too late 
our projects operated as they were designed to we managed 
them just exactly as they were designed to operate ross adkins 
spokesman for the corps in tulsa okla said thursday 
what we do is capture all the water we can to minimize any 
damages downstream when mother nature dumps as much rain as we had 
they the reservoirs took off a heck of a big bump that could 
have gone downstream 
if we had not been here a lot more houses and perhaps lives 
would have been lost 
decisions by the corps on how fast to release water from the 
reservoirs it manages can have a crucial effect on who is flooded 
and how severely a quick release of water through the dams 
floodgates after a heavy rain increases flooding downstream while 
slower release can mean more flooding upstream if the reservoir 
fills up 
