<TEXT>
the federal communications commission has 
reversed a reaganera rule and says it will again consider criminal 
records in evaluating broadcast license applicants 
the fcc in 1986 under thenchairman mark s fowler rewrote its 
characterpolicy rules to consider only felony convictions that 
appeared to have a direct link with an applicants ability to tell 
the truth and comply with commission rules 
also thursday the fcc dropped a proposal to allot broadcast 
licenses by lottery and formally opened an investigation into the 
charges home satellitedish owners must pay to receive network and 
superstation signals 
the characterpolicy revision had been called into question in 
1988 when the fcc renewed the license of williamsburg county 
broadcasting corp to operate wkspam in kingstree sc the 
companys principal owner gregory knop had been convicted of 
conspiracy to distribute cocaine and sentenced to five years in 
prison 
the station had told the commission that knop had a 
nonbroadcastrelated felony conviction and the fcc did not 
investigate further 
the 1986 revision said crimes that shock the conscience or 
misconduct which demonstrates the proclivity of an applicant to 
deal truthfully with the commission and to comply with our rules 
and policies were relevant to licenserenewal proceedings the 
revision did not say whether drug convictions fell into that 
category 
explaining thursdays change fcc chairman alfred sikes said 
that broadcasting pervades and influences our culture and i think 
we must have reasonable standards for holding a license 
under the latest change all felony convictions and some 
misdemeanors will be considered relevant in determining whether a 
party should possess a broadcast license 
the decision was one of several fcc actions designed to tighten 
licensing requirements 
fowler in 1982 legalized unlimited payoffs between competing 
applicants to build stations an action critics said drew a flood 
of nuisance applications from parties simply wanting to be paid off 
to withdraw 
on thursday the fcc proposed to restrict such payoffs perhaps 
to 50 percent of expenses after the licensing process reaches a 
newly proposed settlement conference stage 
the fcc said its action would discourage sham applicants 
the commission also dropped a proposal by fowlers reaganera 
successor dennis patrick to use lotteries to award radio and 
television station licenses 
opponents have said the selection of licensees should not be 
left to a roll of the dice and that such a system would throw open 
broadcasting to unqualified applicants who after gaining a 
license could sell it to the highest bidder 
the lottery proposal also would have ended the existing 
preference in the licensing procedure for applications filed by 
women members of minorities 
in opening the inquiry into prices home satellitedish owners 
pay to get the same signals available to cable television 
companies the commission was following up on its december finding 
of disturbing evidence that cable operators receive 
preferential treatment from satellite tv carriers 
the fcc cited assertions by the national rural 
telecommunications cooperative that some companies may be charging 
backyard dish owners 20 times more than cable tv systems for the 
same programs 
</TEXT>
