<TEXT>
walker percy whose deeply ethical novels 
dealt with displaced southern men searching for faith and love in 
the modern world has died of cancer at age 73 
percys first successful novel the moviegoer won the 
national book award in 1962 it established a theme that would 
occupy his entire career that of spiritually marooned men seeking 
to overcome their alienation 
historian shelby foote a lifelong friend was with percy when 
he died thursday 
he belongs with the great southern writers foote said i 
think he makes a fifth with john crowe ransom william 
faulkner thomas wolfe and eudora welty 
in jackson miss miss welty said im very grieved and very 
very hurt for all his family his friendship meant a lot to me and 
his work meant a great deal to me 
a funeral mass and burial was set for saturday at st josephs 
abbey near covington 
while percys protagonists were in the southern mold his 
philosophical concerns were not the same as other wellknown 
southern writers 
trained as a physician percy converted to catholicism in early 
adulthood during a period of intense personal examination his 
intellectual underpinnings reflected much study of french 
existentialism and he held true to these foundations to his death 
foote said 
he never said why is this happening to me foote said 
nothing like that he tried to reassure his family that this was 
all right 
said miss welty i dont know anybody like him in any way or 
anybody that did have the strong imaginative power and 
philosophical power that he had the scientific power and the 
fictional power all of those twined together into one that is a 
unique quality in his work 
critic stanley kauffmann who edited the moviegoer called 
him one of the loveliest american writers of this century he 
was a natural his novel the moviegoer will last as long as 
america loves literature 
percys other novels included the last gentleman 1966 
love in the ruins 1971 lancelot 1977 the second 
coming 1980 and the thanatos syndrome 1987 
his two major works of nonfiction were the message in the 
bottle 1975 essays on the philosophy of language and lost 
in the cosmos 1983 which he called the last selfhelp book 
percys vision of modern malaise was often ironic hardedged 
and eerily prophetic but his writings also contained some of the 
most wildly comic and deeply humane messages in contemporary 
fiction 
he also taught writing it was through his efforts that john 
kennedy tooles a confederacy of dunces was published 
posthumously the novel won the 1981 pulitzer prize for fiction 
born may 28 1916 in birmingham ala percy was orphaned in 
his teens he and his two brothers went to greenville miss to 
live with william alexander percy his fathers cousin who was 
author of the southern classic lanterns on the levee 
the percy household marked young walker forever with its passing 
parade of intellectuals artists politicians and vagabonds 
percy got a medical degree from columbia university in 1941 the 
next year working as a pathologist at bellevue hospital in new 
york city he caught pulmonary tuberculosis while performing 
autopsies on derelicts 
ive often said that getting a light case of tb was the best 
thing that couldve happened to me it gave me a period of enforced 
idleness percy said 
he read voraciously during his three years of recovery and 
turned to a life of writing 
he often gave credit to his original presbyterian work ethic 
for discipline and steadiness in the mornings he wrote and in the 
afternoons he typed what hed written he did not believe in 
writers block but he was often furiously frustrated 
he told one interviewer its a question of being so pitiful 
god takes pity on you looks down and says hes done for lets 
let him have a couple of good sentences 
its a strange abject littleunderstood profession 
he is survived by his wife mary bernice two daughters mary 
pratt percy lobdell and ann boyd percy moores two brothers leroy 
and billups phinizy percy and four grandsons 
</TEXT>
