battered child who died just two months after he left their home 
maurices adoptive parents bernice and gerald kittelberger are 
charged with seconddegree manslaughter and assault for maurices 
aug 26 1989 death closing arguments in the case are scheduled 
for monday 
maurice was a beautiful baby dale may said thursday outside 
a monroe county courtroom while leafing through photographs of a 
smiling laughing little boy 
another set of photographs those introduced as evidence in the 
kittelbergers trial show a child covered with bruises burns and 
scars 
medical experts testified that maurice had been beaten 
repeatedly and severely with a blunt object a doctor who examined 
maurices body in the emergency room of st marys hospital said 
the childs limbs were so swollen that he could not find a vein to 
inject intravenous medicine 
mrs kittelberger said the child had choked on oatmeal 
monroe county medical examiner nicholas t forbes said the death 
was a direct result of the beatings 
in statements to police the kittelbergers who are black 
said they had hit the child with a belt a paddle and a stick 
wrapped in tape because he had resisted toilet training 
they attributed other injuries an open gash on his forehead a 
tear near his buttocks burn marks on his hands to the child 
tripping and falling or accidentally grabbing mrs kittelbergers 
hot curling iron 
but the mays said maurice was not that kind of child 
while reecie was at our house he was allowed to go 
anywhere may said in two years there were no accidents no 
tripping no falls no anything 
by age 2 maurice was coordinated enough to play computer games 
and an electronic keyboard and knew how to run their videocassette 
recorder mrs may said 
he was smart enough and careful enough that he could turn it 
on she said you never had to worry about reecie touching 
anything getting into anything or bothering anything 
maurice never needed to be scolded or punished the mays said 
an explanation to that child was enough may said a no 
that will hurt you was enough 
the mays who have cared for 20 black and biracial foster 
children over the last three years applied to hamilton county 
ohio officials to adopt maurice 
they told adoption officials that they would enroll maurice in 
an integrated school district and that they would take african 
culture classes so he would not lose his heritage they said they 
would adopt another black child so that maurice would not feel 
isolated when he grew older 
we did every single possible thing to make what we thought was 
a good environment for reecie mrs may said and when they 
said we couldnt have him we did everything we could to make his 
adoption as easy as possible 
the mays said they hope kittelbergers are convicted and 
sentenced to maximum prison terms for destroying maurices life 
the kittelbergers face a maximum of 15 years in prison if convicted 
of the seconddegree manslaughter and assault charges 
moreover the mays are angry with the system that took maurice 
from them and brought him to rochester 
they want to see better investigations of adoptive parents and 
better monitoring to prevent child abuse and they want to see 
arbitrary policies against crossracial adoptions abolished 
love and a wholesome happy environment is important not just 
black and white mrs may said 
</TEXT>
