<TEXT>
pauline frederick an awardwinning broadcast 
reporter who helped pave the way for women in journalism has died 
at the age of 84 
frederick whose married name was pauline frederick robbins 
died wednesday after suffering a heart attack in suburban lake 
forest where she was visiting relatives 
she was the first fullfledged woman correspondent and opened 
doors for womens acceptance in television and radio journalism 
said beryl pfizer a news producer at nbc who worked with 
frederick and beside that she was a heckuva person 
frederick born in gallitzin pa worked for five years as an 
abc correspondent before moving in 1953 to nbc where she served as 
united nations correspondent for 21 years at the un she covered 
events including the cuban missile crisis and chinas entrance into 
the united nations 
frederick once came to the office from a diplomatic dinner 
dressed in a black evening dress to update reports on a situation 
in a foreign country with information she gathered at the dinner 
pfizer recalled thursday 
in 1976 she moderated the second presidential debate between 
gerald ford and jimmy carter the first woman journalist to 
moderate a presidential debate 
she was the first woman to be elected president of the united 
nations correspondents association and was also the first of her 
sex to receive a george foster peabody award for achievements in 
broadcasting 
in 1980 frederick became the first woman to receive the highest 
award of the radiotelevision news directors association 
later in her career she worked as an international affairs 
analyst for national public radio 
frederick received a bachelors degree and a masters degree in 
international law from american university in washington dc 
she was married to the late charles robbins former reporter and 
managing editor of the wall street journal she has no immediate 
survivors 
</TEXT>
