west germany could find itself picking 
up part of the tab for soviet troops based in east germany after 
the two germanys merge their economies this summer bonn officials 
said today 
the officials said preliminary negotiations have started between 
moscow and bonn on an arrangement to use west german marks to 
temporarily cover the living costs for red army troops stationed in 
east germany 
the officials spoke on condition of anonymity 
it appears that the 380000 soviet soldiers in east germany 
could start receiving west german marks for their living costs in 
exchange for soviet rubles after the german economies are merged on 
july 2 
such an agreement would mark the first time a nato country ended 
up paying in its own currency for the stationing of soviet troops 
a west german government spokeman dieter vogel said that 
finance minister theo waigel will travel to east berlin on monday 
to discuss the soviet troops issue with the east german government 
under current bilateral agreements the soviet union buys east 
german marks in exchange for socalled transfer rubles at a 
preferential rate transfer rubles are not convertible to western 
countries 
the east marks are then used to pay for goods and services for 
soviet soldiers stationed in east germany these have been 
relatively inexpensive because of state subsidies 
when the west german mark becomes east germanys official 
currency july 2 east germany will also start to eliminate state 
subsidies that means a new exchange rate will have to be 
established between the west german mark and the soviet transfer 
ruble and the steep price rises anticipated as a result of the 
loss of subsidies will also have to be taken into account 
it remains unclear how much west germany would end up paying to 
maintain the soviet troops or whether the average soviet soldier 
would come out ahead 
a west german government official said the bilateral talks with 
moscow are just at a beginning phase and it is not clear how a new 
arrangement for covering the cost of stationing the soviet troops 
will be worked out 
the official who spoke on condition of anonymity said he did 
not know what the current costs for the soviet troops are 
he said the west germans have not yet seen any concrete 
proposals from the soviet side on how to cover the red armys 
costs 
