<TEXT>
the galileo spacecraft looping through 
the solar system on the way to its 1995 exploration of jupiter 
fired its thrusters today in a major maneuver meant to steer it 
near earth late this year 
were trying to reshape the trajectory slightly so we move 
closer and closer to our aim point near earth on dec 8 said 
neal ausman mission director at nasas jet propulsion laboratory 
galileos tiny rocket thrusters which are small enough to fit 
in the palm of a hand started firing at 1110 am pdt and will 
fire roughly 3000 times by the time the maneuver ends saturday 
afternoon laboratory spokesman jim wilson said 
the twoday maneuver will slow the spacecraft which was 
traveling about 66000 mph earlier today by about 25 mph it also 
will gradually alter its direction ausman said 
it is the second of three or four maneuvers needed to bring 
galileo within 1000 miles of earth which will act as a gravity 
slingshot to help expand the spacecrafts orbit around the sun and 
propel it toward jupiter he added without maneuvers the 
spacecraft would miss earth by 15 million miles 
as of today galileo was 96 million miles from earth but has 
traveled a looping path of 365 million miles since it was launched 
from space shuttle atlantis last oct 18 its trip to jupiter will 
total 24 billion miles 
galileo will make a second swing past earth in december 1992 it 
flew past venus in another gravity slingshot maneuver on feb 9 
in july 1995 the spacecraft separates into a 4890pound 
orbiter and a 760pound probe they are scheduled to reach jupiter 
the solar systems largest planet on dec 7 1995 
the probe will plunge into the planets atmosphere relaying 
measurements to the orbiter before the probe is destroyed by 
intense atmospheric pressure the orbiter will spend at least two 
years studying and taking snapshots of jupiter and its major moons 
europa ganymede and callisto 
</TEXT>
