<TEXT>
the supreme court announced friday the 
selection of 12 organizations that will make the courts opinions 
quickly available via computer beginning june 1 
the organizations will be able to reach thousands of subscribers 
by providing the opinions electronically within minutes after they 
are announced the courts public information office said 
the organizations are the associated press the bureau of 
national affairs commerce clearinghouse the department of 
justice mead data central the national clearinghouse for legal 
services the supreme court opinion network the thomson group 
united press international uunet west publishing and a consortium 
of case western reserve university the national public 
telecomputing network and the interuniversity communications 
council 
each organization will pay the court 500 this year to 
participate and will provide its own computer connection to the 
courts computer system through equipment lent to the court by the 
supreme court opinion network 
the network is a nonprofit consortium that includes as its 
members the american bar association the cspan cable television 
network knightridder mead data united press international and 
the washington post 
