court in 1988 which ruled that a witness whose memory had been 
refreshed by hypnosis had been improperly allowed to testify 
a second trial was put on hold last july after judge william 
gillie ruled that johnstons rights were violated when police 
questioned him for 8 hours without a lawyer present 
gillie also ruled that boots a vest and other clothing taken 
from johnston during the interrogation could not be used as 
evidence the judge said a police officer tried to deceive johnston 
into thinking that he had blood on his boots 
prosecutors tried to link the boots to footprints near where the 
bodies were found 
the 10th ohio district court of appeals on thursday upheld 
gillies decision logan county prosecuter charles gerken then 
decided to drop the charges 
