<TEXT>
the povertyplagued mississippi delta 
needs a broad range of remedies including a regional bank 
expanded medicaid coverage and magnet schools to catch up with the 
rest of america says a report released friday 
the 3 million report to be presented to congress on monday is 
billed as a handbook for action for a region of rich soil and 
struggling farms modern hospitals and dying babies the region is 
home to some of the nations top writers and poorest readers 
the study offers a long list of ambitious goals and broadly 
worded requests for help from federal state and local governments 
businesses religious leaders and just about anyone else who might 
be willing to lend a hand 
but the report by the lower mississippi delta commission makes 
scant mention of where the money might come from to pay for its 
recommendations 
the commmission created by congress in 1988 to prepare a 
10year plan for economic development of the delta wasnt 
responsible for finding sources of funding said commission member 
ed jones 
we dont know where the money is going to come from said 
jones a retired democratic congressman from northwest tennessee 
that wasnt our job 
the report defines the delta as a 219county strip along the 
mississippi river from illinois and missouri to kentucky 
tennessee arkansas mississippi and louisiana 
the studys main recommendations include 
coordination of efforts by federal agencies dealing with 
infants and pregnant women to reduce the high rate of infant deaths 
in the delta 
creation of comprehensive state programs aimed at reducing the 
number of teenage pregnancies 
expansion of medicaid coverage for former welfare recipients 
who find jobs and increased efforts to attract more doctors and 
nurses 
establishment of a regional bank to pay special attention to 
small businesses and those owned by minorities 
revision of federal tax codes to allow firsttime lowincome 
home buyers to set up taxfree savings accounts for down payments 
establishment of model magnet schools in each of the delta 
states and a regional magnet school for math and science 
more money from congress for head start educational programs 
more training for delta farmers trying to keep up with 
advances in agricultural technology 
more loans from the farm credit system and the farmers home 
administration and simplification of the paperwork for such 
transactions 
additional state and federal money for upgrading highways 
throughout the region and for improving rural airports and ports 
coordination of state and federal efforts for reducing 
hazardous waste disposal protecting wetlands and reducing soil 
erosion 
</TEXT>
