<TEXT>
a regionally divided federal appeals court on 
friday issued an emergency order allowing release of water from a 
reservoir in the dakotas into the droughtshrunken missouri river 
the order by the 8th us circuit court of appeals is the latest 
development in a battle between upstream and downstream states over 
water from lake oahe which stretches through the central dakotas 
it allows the army corps of engineers to let water out of the 
lake to raise levels in the missouri a move the corps and the 
downstream states contend is needed to maintain shipping on the 
river 
the 8th circuit order stays a previous ruling by a us district 
judge in bismarck nd which ordered the corps to maintain lake 
levels through june 1 after the spring hatch of walleye pike 
the stay was issued by a threejudge panel of the 8th circuit 
until arguments can be heard on the case the court scheduled those 
arguments for may 16 in st paul minn 
judges george fagg of des moines iowa and pasco bowman of 
kansas city were in favor of granting the emergency stay judge 
roger wollman of pierre sd dissented 
montana and the dakotas want to keep the water where it is in 
lake oahe a 232mile long reservoir that cuts through north and 
south dakota they contend the release would cripple their fishing 
industry and tourism 
iowa nebraska kansas and missouri want the pent up water 
turned loose to keep barge traffic moving and the wheels of 
commerce turning in their states officials from the downstream 
states maintain that drinking water wildlife and power plants 
would suffer in addition to shipping companies 
a spokesman for the corps said releases into the missouri would 
be increased again from both lake oahe and the last dam downriver 
gavins point which is on the south dakotanebraska border 
because of the rain were getting the effect on lake oahe 
will be very modest said paul johnston a spokesman for the 
corps missouri river division in omaha neb 
attorneys from the justice department asked for the stay 
thursday a day after us district judge patrick conmy in 
bismarck nd issued an order to curtail the flow of water into 
the river at the request of the three northern states 
