<TEXT>
the peace corps is undergoing an impressive 
revival as increasing numbers of foreign governments seek the kind 
of lowcost expertise the volunteer agency provides 
in the next 18 months we will enter more countries than were 
entered in the last 18 years combined says paul coverdell the 
former georgia state legislator who has served as peace corps 
director for the past year 
president bush who has stressed the importance of volunteerism 
is a big booster of the peace corps at a time of budget austerity 
bush is showing his commitment by asking for 181 million for the 
peace corps for 1991 a record 16 million increase 
congress also has been supportive partly because of the 20 
former volunteers who have since become lawmakers 
everything seems to be going the peace corps way lately 
internationally governments are showing less interest in ideology 
and more concern about solving human problems for many of them 
the peace corps is a logical place to turn 
the anticommunist evolution in eastern europe last year opened 
up a whole new region from which the peace corps had previously 
been excluded when the agency was created in 1961 east bloc 
countries were asked whether volunteers would be welcome the 
answer no thanks 
with english becoming increasingly accepted as the language of 
international business what better agency than the peace corps to 
fill the need for classes 
everybody wants to learn english coverdell said the peace 
corps also sends out experts in agriculture urban development 
engineering health nutrition and a new area suddenly in vogue 
the environment 
theres no institution ready to do so much for so many for so 
little said coverdell an atlanta businessman and longtime bush 
backer 
after an auspicious beginning under president john f kennedy 
almost 30 years ago the peace corps eventually fell into disfavor 
in the mid 1970s 
enrollment dropped along with the budget watergate and the war 
in vietnam made many qualified young people cynical about serving 
in a government agency and applications fell some volunteers were 
haunted by charges they were cia operatives disguised as dogooders 
even though kennedy early on ordered the cia to stay away from 
the agency 
president nixon stripped the peace corps of its independent 
status making it a part of an umbrella volunteer agency in the 
process the corps lost some of its unique identity the agency 
became independent again in 1982 
the current enrollment 6500 volunteers and trainees is still 
far below the late 1960s high of more than 15000 but coverdell 
predicts that almost 7300 will be serving by the end of 1992 
when coverdell 50 took over in may of 1989 the peace corps 
was operating in 64 countries by the end of this year he expects 
that figure to rise to 76 
volunteers will be at work in hungary and poland in the coming 
weeks and in czechoslovakia in a few months initial contacts with 
bulgaria and romania have been made and even mongolia one of the 
worlds most isolated countries has shown interest latin american 
countries that once shunned the peace corps are now welcoming 
volunteers 
there is broad expansion on every continent coverdell said 
obviously the peace corps can have only a marginal impact on a 
given country the philippines historically has had the largest 
number of volunteers there are about 300 there now but poverty 
remains pervasive afflicting well over half the population 
and as the first peace corps director sargent shriver sees it 
the volunteers not the host country get more out of the 
experience than anyone 
as always peace corps performance is impaired by some 
volunteers who view their twoyear stint less as a commitment to 
the poor than as a chance to see exotic places but not since the 
halcyon days of 1961 has the agencys image been as favorable as it 
is now 
compared with those early years when the ranks of the peace 
corps were dominated by young liberal arts graduates the agency 
projects a grayer appearance nowadays thanks to the 12 percent who 
are over 50 
the average age of all volunteers is 31 a more mature force 
than the one envisioned by nixon who campaigning against kennedy 
in 1960 said the peace corps would become a discredited haven for 
restless youth a kiddy corps as nixon described it 
