<TEXT>
thurgood marshalls place in history was 
assured before he became a member of the supreme court in 1967 now 
his conservative critics long distressed by marshalls liberal 
record say its time for the first black justice to step aside for 
a more youthful energetic successor 
marshall a civil rights pioneer who as a lawyer helped changed 
the nation will be 82 in july he shrugs off questions about 
retirement with customary curmudgeonly humor 
i have a lifetime appointment and i intend to serve it he 
has said numerous times he once told the washington post i 
expect to die at 110 shot by a jealous husband 
for decades before president johnson named him to the high 
court marshall had traveled the nation as the recognized legal 
champion of the poor and the powerless some say he ranks with the 
rev martin luther king jr as a leader in the battle for racial 
equality 
over 23 years as legal director of the national association for 
the advancement of colored people and then as the federal 
governments solicitor general marshall argued 32 cases before the 
supreme court he won 29 
his biggest naacp victory came in the 1954 ruling that declared 
racially segregated public schools unconstitutional 
he changed america said erwin griswold the onetime harvard 
university law school dean and himself a former solicitor general 
when i think of great american lawyers i think of thurgood 
marshall abe lincoln and daniel webster said georgetown 
university law school dean thomas g krattenmaker 
experts agree marshalls legal accomplishments before joining 
the high court far surpass those of any fellow justice it is his 
stature as a justice that has been questioned of late by 
conservative critics 
they say he is losing interest in much of the courts daytoday 
work and delegates too much responsibility to his young law clerks 
former clerks deny it marshall declined to be interviewed for 
this article 
one of the harshest attacks on marshall was penned by terry 
eastland onetime aide to former attorney general edwin k meese 
iii eastland last year wrote in the conservative national review 
one joke has it that if marshall retired at least he wouldnt be 
paid for watching television 
the reference apparently was prompted by earlier reports that 
marshall is a fan of the peoples court and watches the tv show 
in his court office the justice has denied the reports saying 
thats an awful program 
criticism of marshalls supposed work habits are often 
accompanied by questions of his health 
standing 6 feet 2 and overweight marshall shuns exercise he 
had a heart attack in 1976 has suffered from bouts of pneumonia 
and bronchitis he was hospitalized in 1987 with a potentially 
dangerous blood clot in his right foot 
marshall walks slowly and with apparent difficulty family 
members reportedly convinced him a few years ago to stop driving 
he now gets to work in a chauffeurdriven limousine 
former clerks however insist his health is not deteriorating 
georgetown law professor mark tushnet a marshall clerk in 1972 
said he did not look in good health then he doesnt look any 
different now 
tushnet who is writing a biography of marshall also dismissed 
the idea that the increasing dominance of the courts conservatives 
has soured marshall 
he seemed grumpy when i worked with him and he seems grumpy 
now tushnet said 
legal scholars say a succession of conservative court 
appointments has denied the old civil rights fighter the chance 
that was briefly his to shape the law within two years of 
marshalls appointment to a predominantly liberal court chief 
justice warren burger replaced earl warren and the courts 
evolution toward conservatism had begun 
but marshall has been very important in providing visions of 
where the law should go said krattenmaker he has written 
several dissenting opinions that may prove to be persuasive 
marshall and justice william j brennan are the courts most 
consistent liberals and most frequent dissenters 
they stand alone in opposing capital punishment in all 
circumstances press for broader protection for criminal defendants 
and lead the way in supporting affirmative action for minorities 
and women 
marshalls former law clerks call him the courts conscience and 
say his role is one of making sure the other justices realize their 
decisions are affecting real fleshandblood people 
marshall suffers from glaucoma at times it seems he has 
trouble reading summaries of his opinions from the bench at a 
celebration of his 80th birthday he insisted that television 
camera lights be turned off because the glare bothered his eyes 
rumors of declining alertness were fed by an incident last fall 
during an oral argument session before the court 
marshall posed several questions to a lawyer he seemingly 
believed was representing the government when in fact the lawyer 
was representing the other side 
if i appear confused i am marshall said at one point when 
another justice noted whom the lawyer represented marshall 
recovered by telling the lawyer well there is no bar to you 
giving me some help 
marshalls public appearances away from the bench are rare but 
when he does appear he doesnt mince words 
in televised interviews in 1987 he said president reagans 
