<TEXT>
edwin coopermans successes at american express 
co are recounted nightly in commercial television scenes 
theres the toddler who feeds the new videocassette recorder 
gloppy breakfast cereal the traveling executive who loses his 
charge card just before trying to check into a hotel for the night 
the yuppie dad who cancels all appointments and buys a fishing boat 
to take his kid on vacation 
they are stories with happy endings thanks to american express 
and cooperman who as president of the travel related services 
division is the man behind those scenes 
during coopermans three years at the helm of the card division 
american express has introduced such innovations as a global 
assist 24hour help line for cardmembers the optima extended 
payment card and buyer assurance plans guaranteeing charged items 
against loss theft or damage 
the ads pitching these extras arent concocted by copy writers 
they are based on real calls and letters to american express which 
has made service a cornerstone of the card division under cooperman 
trim and slightly graying at 46 cooperman spends a majority of 
his time on the road or in the air visiting the companys 
farflung ofices from beijing to berlin singapore to st louis 
hes not a mastercard or visa holder but keeps five american 
express cards in his wallet platinum gold green corporate and 
optima 
each one has a different use he said my daughter of 
course now she wants five but thats a whole different story 
shell stick with her two 
a lawyer by profession cooperman has been with the company for 
nearly two decades he has an 18yearold cardcarrying daughter in 
college and another 15yearold daughter in high school 
when hes in his 40thfloor corner office overlooking southern 
manhattan cooperman studies the competition intensely collecting 
newspaper and magazine articles about the card business 
he especially enjoys showing visitors a yellowed clipping by 
financial columnist dan dorfman portending the demise of american 
expresss growth it was written 10 years ago 
since that time weve had the greatest growth in our 
history cooperman said 
there has been speculation that coopermans division may feel 
increased pressure to perform now because of weaker sister 
businesses notably shearson lehman hutton inc which has been 
pinched by the recession on wall street and freshly bankrolled by 
its american express parent 
cooperman said hes not overly concerned 
i think were going to run our business as usual but you know 
all the employees and myself we stand a little taller these days 
we want to show the strength of the company he said so i 
guess in that respect we put pressure on ourselves 
coopermans division spends a lot of money by some estimates 
the companys advertising budget is about 250 million more than 
visa and mastercard combined but cooperman is no moneyloser 
rising from relative obscurity in the companys general counsel 
office he has helped make travel related services the most 
profitable part of the company last year for example the 
division earned 830 million on revenue of 84 billion 
by contrast the companys ids financial services unit earned 
175 million american express bank earned 122 million 
information services 83 million and shearson 110 million 
cooperman helped pioneer the push into hightech advancements 
that american express uses to battle visa and mastercard american 
express computers enable it to replace a card anywhere within 24 
hours check a cardmembers credit history instantly and provide 
help ranging from airline tickets to bail money 
even in mundane monthly billing cooperman said american 
express has introduced an imaging technology that provides 
customers with copies of each charge receipt theyve signed 
our competitors give you nothing he said theyve moved 
to just telling you what you bought but not giving you the copy 
back 
competitors have watched the number of american express cards in 
the united states grow to more than 243 million up more than 50 
percent since late 1985 when cooperman took command the card is 
accepted at more than 3 million establishments worldwide more than 
double the number at the end of 1985 
still visa and mastercard remain the dominant plastic in the 
united states with a combined total of about 90 percent of the 
market or more than 200 million cards 
american express may give more they concede but customers pay 
more in membership fees and cannot finance payments unless they 
have an optima card 
financial services analysts say theyre not sure how many 
inroads american express will make into visa and mastercard 
territory nonetheless most express admiration for the card 
division and cooperman 
when you call up american express with a problem you get much 
better service said gary hovis who follows the company for 
argus research corp in new york cooperman he said seems to be 
a very good executive a very hard worker i think hes a plus for 
the business 
bruce brittain head of an atlantabased market research firm 
that studies creditcard use said the quality of service likely 
will remain an advantage for american express over bankissued 
credit cards 
no matter what visa or mastercard promise it boils down to 
what kind of service you get from the issuing bank brittain 
said you always hear about the horror stories theres a real 
advantage to having one central issuer 
the highprofile television ads are a hit with cooperman who 
stresses the factual base for the companys service claims the vcr 
ad for example was based on a letter from the mother of this 
child who told us this incredible story it was a positive letter 
of how pleased she was and how quickly american express helped her 
out and got a new vcr 
not all cardmember feedback is so effusive but cooperman 
displays a sense of humor about the limits of some services such 
as the loststolendamaged guarantee 
obviously anytime you launch a new program like this youre 
not going to think of everything he said 
