<TEXT>
the united states trade deficit is set to 
worsen significantly despite declining surpluses for japan south 
korea and other pacific nations according to a new forecast 
countries around the pacific rim also are poised for a modest 
rebound in growth next year after a selfimposed twoyear slowdown 
designed to rein in inflation said the report released thursday by 
the asia foundation 
japan saw its trade surplus narrow in 1989 despite a sharp 
depreciation in the yen relative to the dollar which makes its 
exports more competitive and imports more expensive 
the countrys trade surplus which declined to 573 billion 
last year from 788 billion in 1988 should drop to 427 billion 
this year before edging up to 455 billion in 1991 according to 
the foundations pacific economic outlook for 199091 
taiwans balance of payments surplus in the region is forecast 
to drop to 104 billion this year and 92 billion in 1991 from 
111 billion last year 
similarly south korea will see its surplus fall from 51 
billion last year to 1 billion this year and 300 million next 
year the report says 
the united states meanwhile is expected to move the other way 
after cutting its balance of payments deficit in the region from 
118 billion in 1988 to 966 billion in 1989 the deficit is 
expected to rise to 105 billion this year and 116 billion in 1991 
the united states can help itself by cutting its own budget 
deficit says lawrence b krause an economics professor at the 
university of californiasan diego who helped produce the report 
but krause sees no likelihood of america regaining a trade surplus 
with japan or the rest of the pacific region in the next few years 
the outlook an important tool used by planners in the region 
is based on analyses and predictions by economists from 15 
countries affiliated with the pacific economic cooperation 
conference 
the regions powerhouses all slowed their economies with tight 
monetary policies to curb inflation 
most countries in latin america africa and southern europe 
would have been happy with the 1989 inflation rates of the 
pacifics leading economies 23 percent in japan 44 percent in 
taiwan 57 percent in south korea and 49 percent in the united 
states as measured by the consumer price indexes 
overall the regions inflation rate was 65 percent a figure 
bloated by rates of 176 percent in china 101 percent in hong 
kong and 106 percent in the philippines 
the tight money policies are expected to bring inflation down in 
1991 to 15 percent in japan 33 percent in taiwan 60 percent in 
south korea and 48 percent in the united states 
the regions overall inflation rate should drop to 55 percent 
next year with china cutting its rate to 95 percent hong kong to 
70 percent and the philippines to 97 percent 
krause said the regions declining growth rate should moderate 
this year and pick up slightly in 1991 
the forecast calls for growth of 50 percent this year down 
from 53 percent in 1989 and 72 percent in 1988 
the forecast has a modest recovery in 1991 up to 52 percent 
so it will have taken two years to moderate the excesses and then 
have some recovery again krause said 
one notable exception from that growth forecast is japan where 
growth is expected to decline from 51 percent in 1989 to 43 
percent in 1990 and 31 percent in 1991 
the united states is expected to remain stuck with one of the 
regions lowest growth rates 30 percent in 1989 25 percent in 
1990 and 28 percent in 1991 
the regions growth leader thailand should slow from a rate of 
11 percent last year to 91 percent this year and 84 percent in 
1991 with singapore and malaysia slightly behind 
chinas political crackdown last year hurt its economy and hong 
kongs but did not have much impact on the rest of the region the 
report said 
