<TEXT>
two investment firms have formed a joint venture 
to manage the money utilities are required to set aside to pay for 
the eventual dismantling of nuclear power plants 
john nuveen amp co inc and duff amp phelps inc have announced 
they have formed nuveenduff amp phelps investment to offer 
investment management services to nuclear utilities 
nuveen spokesman jeff kratz said estimates of the cost of 
decommissioning the nations 110 nuclear power plants range from 
100 billion to 1 trillion 
the cost for an individual utility may not be very great he 
said but we are talking about a very substantial amount of money 
overall 
kratz said nuveenduff amp phelps would advise the utilities on 
how to invest their decommissioning funds 
he noted that nuveen amp co specializes in nontaxable 
investments such as municipal bonds and duff amp phelps specializes 
in taxable fixed income and equity securities the utilities will 
require both kinds of investments to finance the decommissionings 
he said 
we will appear at rate hearings to provide expert testimony on 
what rates of return the utilities are receiving kratz said 
we will act as advisors to utilities keeping them abreast of 
the market and in general be prepared to assist them to meet the 
decommission liabilities 
the nuclear regulatory commission only recently has required 
utilities to set up funds to pay for plant dismantling the 
utilities have until july 26 to show how they will finance the 
shutdowns 
nrc spokesman jan strasma in chicago said the federal agency 
requires the utilities to either prepay the entire decommissioning 
cost into an independent fund establish a sinking fund and pay 
into it gradually or establish a surety bond that guarantees 
payment of decommissioning 
depending on the size and type of plant the utility would have 
to set aside 105 million to 135 million for each reactor 
decommissioning involves taking the fuel out of the plant 
decontaminating the unit and removing the reactor 
the idea is to return the site to pristine condition for other 
uses said cathy roche spokeswoman for the us council of 
energy awareness an industry group based in washington dc it 
is a fairly longterm process 
decommissioning is an expensive process and we want the 
utilities to have sufficient funds to do it strasma said adding 
the funds cannot be used by the utilities for operating expenses 
he said laws vary from state to state on how funds can be 
invested 
under rules established by the illinois commerce commission 
illinoisbased commonwealth edison which operates 13 nuclear 
plants is limited to investing its decommissioning funds in us 
treasury bonds bank certificates of deposits and taxexempt bonds 
comed official debbie vestal noted that in 1989 the utility put 
66 million into the fund which is handled by four investment 
firms including brown brothers harriman amp co of new york 
before 1989 comed integrated its decommission funds into its 
operating fund from which it received a higher rate of return 
the new fund is covered by a different tax bracket which lowers 
the rate of return said ms vestal however she said it is 
difficult to judge how well the investment firms are doing with the 
account because there is nothing to compare it with 
scott peters a spokesman for the us council for energy 
awareness said there are currently no nuclear plants up for 
decommissioning although a number of plants are idle 
but he said the technology exists that could extend the lifetime 
of the plants utilities may find that it is cheaper to refurbish 
plants than replace them he said 
