the lawsuit which was filed in december focused on technology 
known as a graphical user interface which makes computers easier 
to use by replacing typed commands with pictures called icons on 
the screen and a pointer device called a mouse 
the technology helped sell millions of macintoshes and forced 
other manufacturers to offer similar systems for desktop computers 
xerox maintained that many features in the macintosh originated 
at xeroxs palo alto research center about 30 miles south of san 
francisco in the 1970s the suit sought 150 million in damages 
and asked to have apples copyrights on the macintosh display 
technology cancelled 
on march 23 walker dismissed five of xeroxs six counts against 
apple on procedural grounds the remaining count sought a 
declaratory judgement stating that xerox owns the copyright to its 
star program one of those it accused apple of pirating 
xerox said it intends to appeal the dismissal 
