sponsors as dreyfus corp and fidelity investments which lately 
have introduced funds based on stockmarket indexes 
vanguard group a singular early success in the field with its 
index trust500 portfolio is extending the idea to a series of new 
fund offerings 
at the very least a minifad is developing says sheldon 
jacobs publisher of the monthly newsletter noload fund investor 
in hastingsonhudson ny 
if the strategy proves as popular with the public as it has 
among managers of pension funds and other institutional pools of 
money it could turn out to be substantially more than a fad 
index funds are set up to duplicate the performance of some 
popular market yardstick such as standard amp poors 500stock 
composite index by holding a portfolio of issues that closely 
matches the makeup of the index 
this often strikes those who first encounter the concept as 
playing for a tie rather than shooting for allout victory in 
the battle for investment profits 
indeed indexing has never had a big fan club among securities 
analysts economists and market forecasters who compete to 
outguess each other after all the theory behind it pretty much 
dismisses their work as a waste of time and money 
regardless of who is right in this academic debate however 
indexed moneymanagement strategies do appear to have benefited 
from the makeup of the modern marketplace 
when institutions by virtue of their increasingly dominant 
role in effect become synonymous with the market it stands to 
reason that they cannot as a group outperform that market 
also says jacobs over the long run the costs of investing 
can offset managerial skill index funds gain an edge by 
minimizing or eliminating the costs of research and frequent 
trading 
the vanguard 500 portfolio which was started in 1976 has 
attracted assets approaching 2 billion even in todays 1 
trillion fund industry any fund over 1 billion still ranks as a 
big success 
whether you count the 500 portfolio as a growth or growth 
and income fund jacobs says its 165 percent average annual 
return over the past five years is good enough to rank it among the 
top 20 percent of its class 
damning as it may look to the managed competition that showing 
may exaggerate the virtues of indexing to some degree 
the big stocks that make up the sampp 500 have been outpacing 
their smaller counterparts in recent years jacobs notes in part 
because of their popularity among foreign investors and because of 
the spreading use of indexing itself 
whether the bluechip 500 will stay at the head of the pack in 
the 1990s remains an open question some analysts say smaller 
secondary stocks some of which are now being grouped into new 
specialized index funds are due for a comeback 
while the odds favor a change in market leadership it is very 
difficult to say just when this will occur jacobs observes 
to investors shopping for an indexfund investment jacobs 
offers a couple of suggestions first of all he says pay special 
attention to all costs including management fees operating 
expenses and any entrance or exit charges 
the whole point of index fund investing is to minimize 
expenses he says 
secondly he recommends spreading your money among funds based 
on indexes of both large and small stocks that way he 
concludes you really will be guaranteed a market return 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

