<TEXT>
while banks in some areas might be pruning their 
lists of qualified borrowers they are still shoveling out the 
money on credit cards 
the latest federal reserve figures show that revolving credit 
most of it run up at retail stores and through bank cards rose at 
a 121 percent annual rate in march a rather large figure for a 
sluggish economy 
that increase means that in the first quarter of this year the 
amount of consumer debt outstanding was 706 billion or roughly 
24 billion more than existed a year earlier 
most of this credit it is presumed went to pay for new 
consumer items although some cynics will tell you that a good many 
americans these days have become accustomed to meeting ordinary 
expenses through borrowing 
meanwhile business loans socalled commercial and industrial 
loans have been slowing in the first 14 weeks of 1988 campi loans 
rose 101 billion in the same period of 1989 they rose 12 
billion in 1990 they rose just 54 billion 
the federal reserve and other federal regulators leave no 
misimpressions about their goal which is to keep the economy cool 
and collected that is to say they seek to avoid inflation avoid 
recession and get the bills paid 
because of this policy the fed concedes there are pockets of 
tight money a rather odd turn of phrase for what are in effect 
empty pockets but it declines to say that a general credit crunch 
exists 
nevertheless complaints are rising in some areas from small 
businesses especially developers who claim their lines of credit 
are being withdrawn or reduced home mortgage applications also are 
being scrutinized more closely 
while there might or might not be a credit crunch the situation 
obviously concerns the fed which last week advised bankers to act 
like bankers that is to assume prudent risks rather than attempt 
to reduce risk to zero 
meanwhile those bank cards seem to be an exception to the new 
conservatism of lenders banks continue to expand their bank card 
lists and credit limits for customers who pay on time may even be 
raised no questions asked 
the explanation isnt complex bank cards are profitable 
the major reason is that interest charges are often double those 
of home equity loans when some home mortgages are in single 
digits for example many bank card rates are 195 percent plus an 
annual fee 
moreover while the total amount of credit extended on bank 
cards might be sizeable for any particular bank the separate loans 
are relatively small the banks exposure on any one loan is 
limited 
in contrast a home equity loan can be large millions of 
americans own homes that have doubled in value in the past decade 
or less and they are tempted to use that equity home equity loans 
are the least expensive and the expense is made still lower at tax 
time when interest paid can be deducted 
in lending to small businesses meanwhile bankers are 
confronted with this situation smallbusiness loans often are 
risky that risk is made even more so when the economy is sluggish 
many such loans have gone bad in recent years 
confronted with regulatory restraints poor business conditions 
and recent bad experience on loans to small businesses many 
bankers seem to be retreating to the security the limited risk and 
the high returns of bank card credit 
