<TEXT>
leaders of top us businesses said 
friday the economy will grow only moderately this year and next but 
will manage to stave off a recession 
inflation is on the way down they say predicting that the 
firstquarter annual inflation rate of 81 percent will be cut 
nearly in half 
economic growth will total about 2 percent in 1990 as it 
accelerates gradually from 19 percent in the first half of the 
year to 23 percent in the second according to the business 
council 100 chief executives of the nations largest corporations 
it will rise to 26 percent in 1991 
the bush administration forecast in january that the economy 
would grow 24 percent in 1990 although many economists expect 
that to be lowered in the july review it projects 32 percent 
growth in 1991 
the councils latest forecast presented at its semiannual 
meeting at this mountain resort contrasted with a report released 
at its october meeting that predicted a meager 18 percent growth 
rate in 1990 and warned of an outright recession if the federal 
reserve failed to cut interest rates 
the fed which had boosted rates to slow the economy in its 
fight against inflation did permit rates to drop several times 
after the october meeting but it has kept a firm hand on credit 
since december despite calls for easing by administration officials 
and some economists to allow stronger economic growth 
lewis t preston business council vice chairman and chairman of 
