<TEXT>
a federal commission studying the nations 
povertyblighted mississipi delta has recommended development of a 
regional bank to get capital to the areas small and minorityowned 
businesses 
its one of many recommendations in the final report of the 
lower mississippi delta development commission formed by congress 
in 1988 to determine why the resourcerich delta is the poorest in 
the united states the report is to be presented to congress monday 
section iii of the foursection report deals with the problems 
of private enterprise and how best to develop business in the 
region which covers 219 counties in the states of arkansas 
louisiana mississippi missouri illinois tennessee and kentucky 
the delta region as a whole has substantial assets in its 
banking system and these assets currently total about 78 
billion the report noted 
but that money isnt getting to the entrepreneurs who need it 
according to the report 
bank deposits in the region totalled 5992 billion for 1989 
while loans totalled 442 billion for a loandeposit ratio of 736 
percent the report said 
improving that ratio to the national level of 795 percent would 
spur 35 billion in additional investment the report said 
in each of the commissions public hearings delta business 
persons addressed the need for greater access to capital and 
encouraged the delta commission to recommend the establishment of a 
regional funding entity to work with banks to increase the amount 
of capital available for regional investment the report said 
a regional bank could guarantee local bank loans provide equity 
loans and various other types of financing to help small and 
minorityowned businesses get started and help existing businesses 
expand the report said 
the report encourages state and federal governments 
universities chambers of commerce and others to share knowledge 
resources and technology 
and it says too few delta business managers recognize the need 
for or have access to the kind of technology training and 
resources that will strengthen their skills and expertise as 
managers 
the report decries the lack of black business people in the 
delta 
approximately 40 percent of the total population is african 
american yet the involvement of african americans in the business 
sector is far less substantial the report said 
the report also noted that industries in the delta rely too 
heavily on harvesting its rich agricultural and mineral resources 
and too little on making products out of them 
the report notes arkansas success in developing retirement 
communities and suggests other parts of the delta region could do 
the same it also touts tourism for the region suggesting 
development of a tourism entity that could promote the cultural 
diversity and natural beauty of the area and work with amtrak to 
develop a major passenger train corridor through the delta 
