<TEXT>
as the trial of three commodities brokers charged in a 
wideranging probe of corruption commenced in a chicago courtroom 
a group of floor traders in new york engaged in an effort to redeem 
the tainted image of their profession 
the floor brokers and traders association formed a year after 
the futures industry came under intense scrutiny for suspected 
trading abuses wants to administer its own ethics pledge to 
traders 
in addition the organization wants to encourage members to 
attend ethics classes tailored to the moral choices and challenges 
of trading in which fortunes can be made and lost in a few 
minutes time 
although image is a major concern the groups president michael 
wilner says the organization will address other issues such as the 
controversial practice of dual trading which it favors and 
working conditions on the floor of new yorks commodity exchanges 
the association has attracted about 520 members in the past two 
months among them traders at the new york mercantile exchange 
the commodity exchange and the coffee sugar amp cocoa exchange 
wilner president of hilltop trading co said they all have one 
thing in common they are hardworking down to earth guys 
our belief is that the majority of traders are aboveboard 
professionals wilner said and we dont want our image 
hammered by the misdeeds of a few 
in chicago danny l scheck robert d mosky and david zatz are 
on trial in us district court on charges stemming from an fbi 
probe of trading fraud at the chicago mercantile exchange and 
chicago board of trade 
the governments case rests partly on tapes made by an fbi agent 
who secretly recorded conversations while posing in 1988 as a 
corrupt trader in the swiss franc futures trading pit at the 
mercantile exchange 
the government contends the tape recordings reveal a variety of 
schemes employed by the trio to divert customer profits to their 
own accounts 
but defense lawyers say the tapes portray their clients proper 
attempts to verify trades they made with each other and the agent 
amid the hubbub that is typical of a futures trading pit 
wilner said the association wants to change the image of floor 
traders from the public perception of them as brash rich gamblers 
who bet on the future prices of basics ranging from soybeans to 
pork bellies 
the association plans a newsletter to keep traders educated 
about regulatory issues to assure they are in compliance with the 
rules wilner said 
but image is only one concern of the association 
wilner said the group plans to defend dual trading in which 
floor traders execute customer orders and trade for themselves at 
the same time critics say the practice creates enormous 
opportunities for cheating and enables traders to executive 
profitable dealers for themselves before they take care of clients 
the commodity futures trading commission the federal agency 
responsible for policing the futures pits has proposed phasing in 
a dualtrading ban 
dual trading is appropriate wilner said adding that he has 
found that most customers are comfortable with it 
the reason it is an advantage is it ensures a high caliber of 
experience and compensation comes not only from salary and 
commission but from ones own trading account 
quality of life issues are also a concern for the group 
the comex nymex coffee sugar amp cocoa exchange as well as the 
new york futures exchange and the cotton exchange all share the 
same floor space in the world trade center 
the cramped floor space stunts the growth of the exchanges and 
makes the traders jobs more difficult the association hopes to 
have input in the search for larger quarters as well as find 
affordable health insurance for traders wilner said 
