i was here last june its been a sad time to be here in 
china he said but lets not slam the door on them i know 
many chinese people and i have yet to find one who thinks it would 
be helpful to lift mfn 
mostfavorednation status which the united states grants to 
all but a few nations substantially reduces tariffs on goods 
exported to the united states 
without it the us tariff on chinesemade sweaters would rise 
from the current 6 percent to 60 percent the duty on chinese toys 
would go from less than 7 percent to 70 percent the 
washingtonbased uschina business council has estimated 
toys sweaters and other garments accounted for most of chinas 
12 billion in exports to the united states last year which in 
turn comprised nearly onethird of chinas total exports 
with higher tariffs chinese sales to the united states would 
drop at least 50 percent the council predicted 
most us toy and clothing merchandisers could find alternate 
suppliers but for chinese manufacturers there really isnt 
another market said a western economist in beijing speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
their exports to japan and the european community are growing 
very slowly theyre just not going to sell much of this stuff to 
south korea and indonesia he said 
the impact on the chinese economy could be serious especially 
in the exportdriven coastal areas analysts agree 
china has not said how it would retaliate but at a minimum it 
likely would suspend reciprocal preferential tariffs that could 
affect us wheat farmers and fertilizer and airplane 
manufacturers leaders in the united states 57 billion worth of 
exports to china 
us joint ventures in china fear suspending mfn could create so 
much hostility that they would be unable to operate the american 
chamber of commerce predicted problems in getting chinese 
government cooperation essential to obtain loans contracts raw 
materials and even electricity 
recent commentaries in chinas official media have warned that 
political relations would suffer as well 
the us business communitys outcry over the prospect of losing 
the china market comes in sharp contrast to its usual complaints 
