<DOCNO> AP900511-0268 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the worlds largest manufacturer of aircraft 
bolts and fasteners pleaded guilty friday to charges of conspiring 
to falsify test reports on the parts and agreed to pay 18 million 
in penalties and costs 
two former employees of the company vsi corp also pleaded 
guilty to one count each of conspiracy 
the case part of a continuing investigation into wrongdoing in 
the aerospace industry recovered the most money of any action 
stemming from information received under the federal whistleblower 
law us attorney mike mckay said 
under the law three former vsi employees who complained about 
the phony tests will be entitled to share at least 21 million 
mckay said 
for at least 14 years vsi intentionally deceived its 
customers including the us government mckay told a news 
conference vsi did this to cut corners and line its pockets 
parts manufactured by vsi are used throughout the civilian and 
military aircraft industry with about half the companys products 
sold to the government or defense contractors 
mckay said the falsified reports covered millions of fasteners 
including some bought for the b2 b1 and b52 bombers c5b 
transport plane and f18 f15 and f16 fighters 
boeing spokesman paul binder said the fasterners are used on 
virtually every boeing product including civilian airliners 
no accidents have been traced to faulty fasteners said 
assistant us attorney bruce carter who prosecuted the case 
before us district judge barbara rothstein vsi pleaded guilty 
to three counts of mail fraud and one count of conspiracy to commit 
mail fraud provide false statements to the government and defraud 
the united states the pleas were entered by company vice president 
donald s parker 
james e ryan a former quality assurance manager at vsis 
voishan plant in chatsworth calif and aram marderian a former 
metallurgical laboratory supervisor for voishan also pleaded 
guilty to one count each of conspiracy 
rothstein set sentencing for aug 17 ryan and marderian both 
of whom have agreed to cooperate in further government 
investigations each face up to five years in prison and up to 
250000 in fines 
as part of the plea agreement vsi agreed to pay a fine of 25 
million and the estimated 1 million for the costs of the 
investigation 
to resolve a separate civil whistleblower case vsi will make an 
additional payment of 145 million the three whistleblowers will 
share 15 percent to 25 percent of that mckay said 
vsi a subsidiary of fairchild industries inc and ryan and 
marderian were charged wednesday 
the government alleged that from 1975 or earlier to february 
1989 some required tests were omitted test results were altered 
parts were reworked in violation of specifications and falsified 
reports were given by vsi to boeing northrop mcdonnell douglas 
lockheed general electric pratt amp whitney the defense department 
and other customers 
the stamp of a fictitious inspector 11 was used to indicate 
that some tests had been completed successfully the complaint said 
some bolts that failed tests were delivered with documents 
indicating they met specifications and other required tests 
werent performed the complaint said in other instances tests 
were performed on fewer parts than required 
the mail fraud charges involved phony test results provided to 
boeing at seattle and wichita kan general dynamics in fort 
worth texas and northrop in los angeles carter said 
vsi will cooperate fully with the government and wants to put 
all this behind it parker said 
if anyone out there is not identified as a wrongdoer were 
going to cooperate to bring them to justice he said 
parker said senior management at the company didnt find out 
about the fraud until february 1989 when federal agents raided the 
voishan plant 
but lawrence finegold an attorney for ryan said his client had 
been following an inherited practice that had gone on for years 
carter said evidence in the case indicated quality control 
fraud really was a way of life at the chatsworth plant 
the probe was triggered by a complaint from whistleblower tom 
runion shortly after he left his job in the metallurgical 
laboratory at the chatsworth facility carter said runion and two 
others are plaintiffs in the whistleblower suit that was unsealed 
friday in us district court in los angeles carter said 
he said inadequate voishan parts were found during aircraft 
assembly and installation and were returned to the manufacturer but 
investigators do not know whether there have been any imminent 
safety threats 
investigators learned that of the government and civilian buyers 
of voishan fasteners boeing and northrop corp especially had 
been rejecting substantial deliveries after doing their own tests 
boeing said it has inspected and tested the fasteners and 
retested certain lots of materials it said voishan materials met 
all boeing specifications and requirements and use of them has 
not compromised the integrity of boeing products 
</TEXT>
