<TEXT>
amax inc the nations thirdlargest coal 
producer made a 125 billion offer friday for industry leader 
peabody holding co raising the possibility of a bidding war with 
a major peabody investor 
he bid was rejected immediately by hanson industries which owns 
45 percent of peabody and is attempting to buy the rest hanson 
responded by raising its offer for the peabody shares it doesnt 
own 
the remaining 55 percent of st louisbased peabody is owned by 
newmont mining corp of denver hanson in turn owns 49 percent of 
newmont 
hanson in march offered to buy newmonts stake in peabody for 
715 million but under terms of the sale agreement between hanson 
and newmont the companies agreed to consider outside bids for all 
of peabody until the deal with hanson closed 
closing tentatively was scheduled for sometime next month said 
newmont spokesman james hill 
after new yorkbased amax disclosed its bid friday hanson 
immediately increased its offer for newmonts peabody stake to 
7256 million that tops the 7185 million that newmonts stake 
is worth under the amax offer hanson said 
hill said newmonts agreement to sell its peabody stake to 
hanson remained in effect but that the amax bid started an auction 
process for peabody 
it is to ensure that the highest bidder gets it he said 
hanson the us arm of britains hanson plc conglomerate 
acquired its peabody stake in february for about 504 million from 
boeing co bechtel investments inc and the energy company eastern 
enterprises 
although their amaxs bid would benefit hanson by providing 
a premium for the stake which we already own we are determined to 
complete our acquisition of peabody said sir gordon white 
chairman of hanson industries 
hanson industries acquired its 49 percent stake in newmont 
through its purchase of consolidated gold fields plc the british 
gold mining company in 1989 
amax which also is a major aluminum producer has said for some 
time that it plans to increase its coal holdings said spokesman 
mitchell badler 
he said peabody would help boost amaxs already substantial 
reserves in lowsulfur coal which is in demand because it pollutes 
less than highsulfur varieties 
we thought it was a good fit he said 
he said amax envisioned no antitrust concerns in its bid because 
of the fragmented nature of the coal industry an amaxpeabody 
combination would control less than 12 percent of the nations coal 
production he said 
badler said he did not know whether amax would increase its bid 
in light of hanson raising its offer 
newmont decided to put peabody up for sale after it failed to 
carry out a restructuring of the coal company hill said 
newmont took on a heavy debt load in 1987 after it paid out a 
special 22 billion dividend to shareholders to avoid a takeover 
from t boone pickens it has been selling assets to reduce the 
debt and also planned to have peabody issue junk bonds and pass 
along some of the proceeds to newmont hill said 
but that plan fell through when the junk bond market went sour 
last year he said 
in consolidated trading friday on the new york stock exchange 
hanson plcs american depositary receipts rose 62 cents to 
1887 newmont shares rose 62 cents to 46 and amax shares fell 
12 cents to 2525 
</TEXT>
